One of the more obscure photos from 2022 from San Fransisca by Vaillancourt fountain by embarcadero plaza. The project was designed to funnel through 115.000 liters of water every minute, creating irregular waterfalls tumbling from the square profiles. The water stopped 2014 due to drought and reactived in 2017 with blue water to clean it. Now it is green But that I can’t explain. The man sleeping might be part of 8000 homeless people in SF and there has been waves of homelessness in this constant changing city. #sanfrancisco #vaillancourtfountain #brutal_architecture #vaillancourtconcrete #brutalismarchitecture @brutgroup @brutal_architecture @newbrutalism

Project Pressure’s exhibition MELTDOWN is coming to KühlhausBerlin
Since 2008, the climate change charity Project Pressure has been commissioning world-renowned artists to conduct expeditions to document changes to the world’s vanishing glaciers.
Featuring images from all seven continents, the exhibited works range in scale from the planetary level to the microscopic biological impact, with artistic interpretations giving an unique insight into the world’s cryosphere, its fragile ecosystem, and our changing global climate.
The series of artworks includes artist Peter Funch’s use of vintage postcards as a model for his images of American glaciers to capture the effects of glacial recession; Norfolk + Thymann’s images of part of the Rhône glacier covered in geo-thermal cloth to limit melting; Richard Mosse’s photograph of the ice cave under the Vatnajökull glacier in Iceland; and Noémie Goudal’s large-scale photographic installation mirroring the shifting glacial landscape, printed on biodegradable paper.
The show will open on February 17th 2023 – please join us!
MELTDOWN: Visualising Climate Change
17 February – 5 March 2023
OPENING HOURS
Tuesday – Saturday
12.00 – 18.00
Kühlhaus Berlin, Luckenwalder Straße 3, 10963 Berlin, Germany @projectpressure @kuehlhausberlinofficial #theimperfectatlas

The Meltdown exhibition was initiated by the charity Project Pressure, which has set itself the task of visualizing the climate crisis. They use art as a positive point of contact to inspire action and behavioral change. In contrast to forest fires and floods, glaciers are not part of the weather system, and if you look at the mass loss of glaciers over time, you can see the result of global warming. This makes glaciers key indicators of the climate crisis and the focus of our work.

Since 2008, Project Pressure has commissioned world-renowned artists to undertake expeditions around the world to create an exhibition to visualize the climate crisis. In the exhibition are e.g. Artists represented: Renate Aller (D), Corey Arnold (USA), Broomberg & Chanarin (South Africa), Edward Burtynsky (Canada, Peter Funch (Denmark), Noémie Goudal (France), Adam Hinton (Great Britain), Richard Mosse (Ireland), Simon Norfolk (Nigeria), Klaus Thymann (Den

The artists have taken on the role of researchers who explore the increasingly unstable environment of the earth - and have created eye-opening works to initiate social and political change. The projects were developed and carried out in cooperation with scientists to ensure accuracy so that works from all continents of the world are represented.

After MELTDOWN was recently seen at the Nelson Provincial Museum in New Zealand, the journey continues - this time to Berlin.

MELTDOWN has traveled around the world in recent years to inform gallery and museum visitors about the always topic of man-made climate change. This time, the exhibition will be even more interactive, as Kühlhaus Berlin organizes discussion evenings, artist dinners and artist talks together with Project Pressure. All events take place between the 17th. February and the 5th March 2023. @projectpressure @kuehlhausberlinofficial

Anne Mikoleit & Moritz  purckhauer writes in urban code”street vendors have developed an unsurpassed business instinct for this. They can be found wherever many people come together in a dense space. They have long recognized that people passionately enjoy making their way across sunny sidewalks. Therefore they place them-selves, according to the time of day, in the sun-light. There, lined up densely, they offer up their goods. As soon as their wares are caught by the shade, they change their position and follow the path of the sun onward. However, where so many street vendors of this type are concentrated on sidewalks, as in the New York district of SoHo, the total mobility of sellers is limited, such that the light of the sun only temporarily touches their wares. Inevitably, then, a tion arises for the most sought-after spots. Long before the first pedestrians populate the side-walk, the sellers mark off their territories from one other. One can even observe vendors ccu-pying spots that are first touched by the warm rays of sunlight in early afternoon, when the density of passersby reaches its peak.
Counterintuitive as it may seem, street vendors have a positive effect on pedestrian circulation.
Not only do vendors act as a buffer between pedestrians and vehicular traffic, they provide people with visual and acoustic reference points that contribute to pedestrians' sense of securi-ty. Through their bargaining and banter, street vendors produce a kind of live street theater, relieving passersby of stress and rendering them amused observers.
A city street equipped to handle strangers, and to make a safety asset, in itself, out of the presence of strangers, as the streets of successful city neighborhoods always do, must have three main qualities: ... And third, the sidewalk must have users on it fairly continuously, both to add to the number of effective eyes on the street and to induce the people in buildings along the street to watch the sidewalks in sufficient numbers.
(Jane Jacobs, The Death and Life of Great American Cities.)

INDEX NATURAE – Skinnerboox
Index Naturae brings together 116 photobooks published in the last five years on the theme of nature, collected and displayed on the occasion of the exhibition of the same title presented at OMNEFEST 2023. Excluding a priori the geographical limit, the research proposes experiences on the theme of five continents that find a specific reference in the origin of the author involved or in the place of investigation. This book is a sort of encyclopedic book, a “book of books” in which every entry, that is, every book, offers itself as a tool capable of suggesting different trajectories of interpretation of nature, of its constituent elements and the relationship that man has with them today. Index Naturae therefore suggests a system of unexpected relationships that – as Gianfranco Baruchello states – simulates the complexity of the associative processes of the mind. In this sense, if the photo–of–photo on the one hand generates a loss of quality, on the other increases the conceptual potential of the images.
Curated by Stefania Rössl, Massimo Sordi
Designed by Damiano Fraccaro / Otium
Publisher Skinnerboox
ISBN 978-88-94895-68-1
